            <fr:p>If the conditions of <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.2.1" href="sga1-i.2.1.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.2.1" /> are satisfied, then we say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>quasi-finite</fr:em> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
  A morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> is said to be quasi-finite at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> (or the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>-prescheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is said to be quasi-finite at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>) if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_x]]></fr:tex> is quasi-finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{f(x)}]]></fr:tex>.
  This is equivalent to saying that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>isolated in its fibre <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(x)]]></fr:tex></fr:em>.
  A morphism is said to be quasi-finite if it is quasi-finite at each point.
  (In [EGA II 6.2.3] we further suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is of finite type.)</fr:p>
